      "keyInformation": [
        "**Classification of Matter**:\n- **Elements**: Pure substances with one type of atom (e.g., Fe, O2).\n- **Compounds**: Two or more elements chemically bonded in fixed ratio (e.g., H2O). Properties differ from constituent elements.\n- **Mixtures**: Physical combination. Components retain properties. Can be Homogeneous (uniform) or Heterogeneous (non-uniform).\n\n**Significant Figures **(Sig Figs)\nThe digits that carry meaning regarding precision.\n1. All non-zero digits are significant.\n2. Zeros between non-zeros are significant.\n3. Leading zeros (0.05) are NOT significant.\n4. Trailing zeros after a decimal point ARE significant (e.g., 2.50).\n\n**Laws of Chemical Combination**:\n1. **Law of Conservation of Mass**: Matter is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction. Total mass of reactants = Total mass of products.\n2. **Law of Definite Proportions**: A pure compound always contains the same elements combined in the same proportion by mass (e.g., Water: 1g H : 8g O)."
